Scope of the Standard

Shunyaya Structural Computation Core (SSC-Core) defines a deterministic structural computation framework governing stepwise execution under replay-verifiable discipline.

SSC-Core establishes:

Conservative collapse invariant:

phi((m,a,s)) = m

Deterministic structural work field:

Psi(t) = W_allow(t) / W(t)

Deterministic structural compression:

Omega = sum_{i=1..N} (1 - Psi(i))

Deterministic structural curvature:

K = sum_{i=2..N} |g(i) - g(i-1)|

Deterministic structural fingerprint:

F = sha256(g_stream || '|' || Psi_samples || '|' || Omega || '|' || K)

Replay identity discipline:

B_A = B_B

SSC-Core does not:

• modify classical computation
• redefine domain equations
• alter measured magnitude
• introduce predictive models
• perform probabilistic inference
• simulate future states
• inject control authority
• guarantee safety outcomes

SSC-Core computes structural geometry of deterministic execution only.

Execution traces used for structural computation may originate from any deterministic execution environment, including optional extensions such as SSC-ISA (Shunyaya Structural Computation Instruction Set).
Such environments generate traces but do not modify the normative structural model defined by SSC-Core.


Conformance

An implementation conforms to the SSC-Core Open Standard if it:

• Preserves magnitude exactly:
phi((m,a,s)) = m

• Uses deterministic structural work accounting

• Computes Psi(t), Omega, K, and F deterministically

• Ensures all structural invariants are trace-derived

• Produces byte-identical artifacts under independent replay:
B_A = B_B

• Avoids probabilistic or tolerance-based arbitration

Any implementation introducing:

• randomness
• probabilistic inference
• adaptive thresholds
• predictive extrapolation
• tolerance-based comparison
• nondeterministic output ordering
• dynamic work model mutation
• magnitude modification

does not conform to the SSC-Core Open Standard.

Independent implementations are permitted and encouraged.


